description: From Middle English leef, from Old English lēaf, from Proto-West Germanic *laub, from Proto-Germanic *laubą (“leaf”), from Proto-Indo-European *lowbʰ-o-m, from *lewbʰ- (“leaf, rind”)

See also West Frisian leaf, Low German Loov, Dutch loof, German Laub, Danish løv, Swedish löv, Norwegian Nynorsk lauv, Icelandic lauf; also Irish luibh (“herb”), Latin liber (“bast; book”), Lithuanian lúoba (“bark”), Albanian labë (“rind”), Latvian luba (“plank, board”), Russian луб (lub, “bast”).
(Internet slang: Canadian): In reference to the maple leaf as national symbol.

entries.meaning: The usually green and flat organ that represents the most prominent feature of most vegetative plants.
Anything resembling the leaf of a plant.
A sheet of a book, magazine, etc (consisting of two pages, one on each face of the leaf).
A sheet of any substance beaten or rolled until very thin.

examples: Heretofore advertisers have had to buy and pay for a leaf — two pages.

entries.meaning: A flat section used to extend the size of a table.
(plural leaves or leafs) A moveable panel, e.g. of a bridge or door, originally one that hinged but now also applied to other forms of movement.
examples: The train car has one single-leaf and two double-leaf doors per side.

entries.meaning: (botany) A foliage leaf or any of the many and often considerably different structures it can specialise into.
(computing, mathematics) In a tree, a node that has no descendants.
examples: The algorithm pops the stack to obtain a new current node when there are no more children (when it reaches a leaf).

entries.meaning: The layer of fat supporting the kidneys of a pig, leaf fat.
One of the teeth of a pinion, especially when small.
(Internet slang, humorous, sometimes pejorative, plural leafs) A Canadian person.

verbs.description: leaf (third-person singular simple present leafs, present participle leafing, simple past and past participle leafed)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To produce leaves; put forth foliage.
(transitive) To divide (a vegetable) into separate leaves.
examples: The lettuce in our burgers is 100% hand-leafed.
